In article <351sdl$ncq@mycroft.rand.org>,
jim@mycroft.rand.org (Jim Gillogly) wrote:
> The PK people might be surprised to know that known plaintext isn't hard
> to come by in actual practice.  For example, if Paul were trying to break
> a ZIP-encrypted C program, he might look for common C strings like
> "\n#include <stdio.h>\n" or "\nmain(argc, argv)\nint argc;\nchar *argv[];\n"

Aww, PKZip always compresses before encrypting.

So I think there is one more obstacle to known-plaintext attacks.

Then again, the details of the compression, e.g. the symbol tables,
Huffman trees, etc. lends a hand to the cryptanalyst.

